# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] Born in Lehe, near Bremerhaven, he started his studies at Marburg University.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] For his PhD, he joined the working group of the Nobel laureate Adolf Windaus at the University of Göttingen and he finished his studies with a PhD in chemistry in 1927.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] His doctoral research was on the chemistry of the insecticidal toxin found in the roots of *Derris elliptica* which he isolated and characterized.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] After his Habilitation he became lecturer in Göttingen 1931.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] He became a professor ordinarius at the Technical University of Danzig from 1933 until 1936.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] In 1933, Butenandt signed the *Vow of allegiance of the Professors of the German Universities and High-Schools to Adolf Hitler and the National Socialistic State*.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] In 1936, he applied for the directorship of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institut (later the Max Planck Institute for Biochemistry) in Berlin-Dahlem while also joining the NSDAP on 1 May 1936 (party member No.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] The earlier director of the Kaiser Wilhelm institute was Carl Neuberg, who had been removed for being a Jew.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] His work on rotenones was considered useful by the Nazi leadership as it could be useful for controlling lice among soldiers in the trenches.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] As the head of a leading institute, he applied for government funding on concentrated research labeled *kriegswichtig* (important for the war), some of which focused on military projects like the improvement of oxygen uptake for high-altitude bomber pilots.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] Adolf Windaus and Walter Schöller of Schering gave him the advice to work on hormones extracted from ovaries.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] This research lead to the discovery of estrone and other primary female sex hormones, which were extracted from several thousand liters of urine.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] In 1940 he was involved in research on a hormone treatment to make long submarine voyages more comfortable for submariners in the Kriegsmarine.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] Butenand's involvement with the Nazi regime and various themes of research led to criticism after the war, and even after his death the exact nature of his political orientation during the Nazi era has never been fully resolved.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] When the institute moved to Tübingen in 1945 he became a professor at the University of Tübingen.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] In 1948, he was considered for the chair for physiological medicine at the University of Basel.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] He entered in negotiations but eventually was convinced by the chemical industry to stay in Germany.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] In 1956, when the institute relocated to Martinsried, a suburb of Munich, Butenandt became a professor at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] He also served as president of the Max Planck Society for the Advancement of Science following Otto Hahn from 1960 to 1972.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] Butenandt is credited with the discovery and naming of the silkworm moth pheromone Bombykol in 1959.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] Butenandt died in Munich in 1995, at the age of 91.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/adolf-butenandt] His wife Erika, born in 1906, died in 1995 at 88.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Elizabeth Anne Cutler was born on 17 January 1945 in Armadale, Victoria.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] She attended the University of Melbourne, and in 1964 received her Bachelor of Arts in Psychology and German.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Two years later she received her Diploma of Education in Modern Languages, and in 1971 received her master's degree in German linguistics.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Cutler embraced psycholinguistics when it emerged as an independent field, going on to complete her PhD in the discipline at the University of Texas at Austin with her dissertation *Sentence stress and sentence comprehension*.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] After postdoctoral research fellowships at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) and the University of Sussex, she worked as a research scientist at the Medical Research Council (United Kingdom) (MRC) Applied Psychology Unit at the University of Cambridge.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Subsequently, she became Professor of Comparative Psycholinguistics at Radboud University.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] In 1993, she became a Director at the Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics in Nijmegen, the Netherlands, and held that title until 2012.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Her research, summarised in the book *Native Listening*, centres on human listeners' recognition of spoken language, and in particular on how the brain's processes of decoding speech are shaped by language-specific listening experience.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Cutler was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 2015 for her work on sentence processing and phoneme recognition.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Cutler was elected as Foreign Member of the American Philosophical Society in 2007 and Foreign Associate of the National Academy of Sciences in 2008.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] In Australia, she was elected as Honorary Fellow of the Australian Academy of the Humanities in 2008 and as Fellow of the Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia in 2009.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] In 2000 Cutler was elected member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] Her work has also received the 1999 Spinoza Prize of the Netherlands Organisation for Scientific Research and the International Speech Communication Association Medal.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/anne-cutler] In 2020 she was elected a Fellow of the British Academy (FBA) and she received the Silver Medal in Speech Communication from the Acoustical Society of America (ASA).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/antje-meyer] Meyer was elected member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences (KNAW) in 2018.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/antje-meyer] In 2018 she also became a member of the German Academy of Sciences Leopoldina.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] Born to an upper-middle-class family of scientists and artists in Frankfurt, List is a great-grandson of the cardiologist Franz Volhard and a 2nd great-grandson of the chemist Jacob Volhard.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] His aunt, the 1995 Nobel laureate in medicine Christiane Nüsslein-Volhard, is the sister of his mother, architect Heidi List.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List obtained his Diplom (M.Sc.) degree in chemistry from the Free University of Berlin in 1993, and his PhD from Goethe University Frankfurt in 1997.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] His doctoral dissertation was titled *Synthese eines Vitamin B 12 Semicorrins* (Synthesis of a Vitamin B 12 Semicorrin), and was advised by Johann Mulzer.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List worked at the Scripps Research Institute Department of Molecular Biology in La Jolla, US as a postdoctoral researcher in Carlos F.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] Barbas III and Richard Lerner's research groups from 1997 to 1998 with a scholarship from the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation and as an assistant professor from 1999 to 2003.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] In 2003 he returned to Germany to become group leader at the Max Planck Institute for Coal Research, and in 2005 he became one of the institute's directors, heading the Homogeneous Catalysis Department.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] He served as the institute's managing director from 2012 to 2014.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] He has held a part-time position as an honorary professor of organic chemistry at the University of Cologne since 2004.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List is also a principal investigator at the Institute for Chemical Reaction Design and Discovery, Hokkaido University since 2018.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] He is the editor-in-chief of the scientific journal *Synlett*.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] As of 2021, he has an h-index of 95 according to Google Scholar and of 86 according to Scopus.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List is considered to be one of the founders of organocatalysis, which uses non-metal and non-enzyme catalysts.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] In particular, while still an assistant professor he discovered the possibility of using the amino acid proline as an efficient chiral catalyst.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] This takes place in intermolecular aldol reactions, in which carbon atoms from two different molecules are bonded together, induced by proline.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] The development is based on the Hajos–Parrish–Eder–Sauer–Wiechert reaction.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] Subsequently, he developed the first proline-catalyzed Mannich, Michael, and α-amination reactions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] He found asymmetric catalysis (especially Asymmetric counteranion directed catalysis, ACDC).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] He developed also new methods of textile organic catalysis, in which soluble organic catalysts and textiles are bound.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] These methods could, for example, help to treat water where there is no fresh water.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] Asymmetric organocatalysis is particularly important in bioactive organic compounds, where the chirality of the compounds is important, for example in drug production.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List married Sabine List in La Jolla in 1999 and they have two sons, Theo and Paul.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] They all survived the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/benjamin-list] List's parents sought to raise their children with an anti-authoritarian parenting style; he has admitted occasionally using the approach with his own children, stating that "you may only be 12, but if you think it will do you good to eat ten chocolate bars, then go ahead and do it.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Sakmann was born in Stuttgart, the son of Annemarie (née Schaefer), a physical therapist, and Bertold Sakmann, a theater director.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Sakmann enrolled in Volksschule in Lindau, and completed the Wagenburg gymnasium in Stuttgart in 1961.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] He studied medicine from 1967 onwards in Tübingen, Freiburg, Berlin, Paris and Munich.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] After completing his medical exams at LMU Munich, he became a medical assistant in 1968 at LMU Munich, while also working as a scientific assistant (Wissenschaftlicher Assistent) at Munich's Max-Planck-Institut für Psychiatrie, in the Neurophysiology Department under Otto Detlev Creutzfeldt.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1971, he moved to University College London, where he worked in the Department of Biophysics under Bernard Katz.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1974, he completed his medical dissertation, under the title *Elektrophysiologie der neuralen Helladaptation in der Katzenretina* (*Electrophysiology of Neural Light Adaption in the Cat Retina*) in the Medical Faculty of Göttingen University.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Afterwards (still in 1974), Sakmann returned to the lab of Otto Creutzfeldt, who had meanwhile moved to the Max Planck Institute for Biophysical Chemistry in Göttingen.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Sakmann joined the membrane biology group in 1979.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1990, he accepted a position at the Faculty of Natural Science Medicine at Heidelberg University.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] One year later, he became a full university professor at the Faculty of Biology in Heidelberg.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] On 2 June 2009, Peter Gruss, the president of the Max Planck Society, announced that Sakmann would serve as the scientific director of the Max Planck Florida Institute, the organization's biomedical research facility at Florida Atlantic University in Jupiter, Florida.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Sakmann is the founder of the Bert-Sakmann-Stiftung.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1986, Sakmann and Erwin Neher were awarded the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize from Columbia University.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1987, he received the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize of the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft, which is the highest honour awarded in German research.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] Gerard Prize in Neuroscience, the Harvey Prize and the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine along with Neher, with whom he had worked in Göttingen.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] In 1993 he became a member of the German Academy of Sciences Leopoldina.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bert-sakmann] He was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1994.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] The **Bibliotheca Hertziana – Max Planck Institute for Art History** is a German research institute located in Rome, Italy.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] It was founded by a donation of Henriette Hertz in 1912 as a Kaiser Wilhelm Institute.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Of the 84 institutes in the Max Planck Society (Max Planck Gesellschaft), it is one of the few not located in Germany.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] The Bibliotheca Hertziana was founded in 1913 in Rome as an institute of the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Society for research on Italian art from the period immediately following antiquity, and in particular the Renaissance and the Baroque periods.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Today, the Bibliotheca Hertziana – Max Planck Institute for Art History is part of the Human Sciences Section of the Max Planck Society and promotes scientific research in the field of Italian and global history of art and architecture.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Under the present directors Tanja Michalsky and Tristan Weddigen, the research carried out at the Institute has broadened its methodological, historical, and geographical horizons.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Tanja Michalsky’s department, Cities and Space in Premodernity, focuses on Southern Italy, specifically Naples and the Mediterranean region, and explores historical concepts of space and their transformation in Premodernity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Tristan Weddigen’s department, Art of the Modern Age in a Global Context, investigates the global ramifications of Italian art from the Early Modern Period to Modernism, questions materiality and mediality, the intellectual history of the discipline of art history, and on digital art history.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] The research group Visualizing Science in Media Revolutions, led by Sietske Fransen, Ph.D., investigates how the representation of scientific images has been influenced by media revolutions and the invention of new instruments and techniques.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] The Lise Meitner Group Decay, Loss, and Conservation in Art History, led by Francesca Borgo, Ph.D., focuses on the decay and loss of artworks and examines how the fragility of objects shapes the way we handle, think, and write about them.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] Regular workshops on current projects, lectures, study courses for younger academics as well as symposia and congresses provide opportunities for academic exchange between the members of the institute and guests from outside.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/bibliotheca-hertziana-max-planck-institute-for-art-history] In addition, innovative database projects on art history were developed early -Cipro, Lineamenta - which are being continued in the various projects of today's Digital Humanities Lab.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroimaging is sometimes confused with neuroradiology.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroradiology is a medical specialty that uses non-statistical brain imaging in a clinical setting, practiced by radiologists who are medical practitioners.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroradiology primarily focuses on recognizing brain lesions, such as vascular diseases, strokes, tumors, and inflammatory diseases.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In contrast to neuroimaging, neuroradiology is qualitative (based on subjective impressions and extensive clinical training) but sometimes uses basic quantitative methods.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Functional brain imaging techniques, such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), are common in neuroimaging but rarely used in neuroradiology.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroimaging falls into two broad categories: structural and functional neuroimaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Structural neuroimaging is used to quantify and provide detailed images of brain anatomy such as structural MRI, and voxel-based morphometry.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Functional neuroimaging is used to study brain function, often using fMRI, positron emission tomography (PET), and magnetoencephalography (MEG).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The early beginnings in the history of neuroimaging trace back to the Italian neuroscientist Angelo Mosso who invented the 'human circulation balance', which could non-invasively measure the redistribution of blood during emotional and intellectual activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In 1918, the American neurosurgeon Walter Dandy introduced the technique of ventriculography.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] X-ray images of the ventricular system within the brain were obtained by injection of filtered air directly into one or both lateral ventricles.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Dandy also observed that air introduced into the subarachnoid space via lumbar spinal puncture could enter the cerebral ventricles and also demonstrate the cerebrospinal fluid compartments around the base of the brain and over its surface.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This technique was later called pneumoencephalography.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In 1927, Egas Moniz introduced cerebral angiography, whereby both normal and abnormal blood vessels in and around the brain could be visualized with great precision.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In the early 1970s, Allan McLeod Cormack and Godfrey Newbold Hounsfield introduced computerized axial tomography (CAT scanning) now known as computed tomography (CT scanning), and ever more detailed anatomic images of the brain became available for diagnostic and research purposes.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Cormack and Hounsfield won the 1979 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine for their work.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Soon after the introduction of CAT in the early 1980s, the development of radioligands allowed single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) and positron emission tomography (PET scan)s of the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] More or less concurrently, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI or MR scanning) was developed by researchers including Peter Mansfield and Paul Lauterbur, who were awarded the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 2003.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In the early 1980s MRI was introduced clinically, and during the 1980s a huge advance in technical refinements and diagnostic MR applications took place.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In the early 2000s, the field of neuroimaging reached the stage where limited practical applications of functional brain imaging have become feasible.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The main application area is crude forms of brain–computer interface.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The world record for the spatial resolution of a whole-brain MRI image was a 100-micrometer volume (image) achieved in 2019.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The sample acquisition took about 100 hours.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The spatial world record of a whole human brain of any method was an X-ray tomography scan performing at the ESRF (European synchrotron radiation facility), which had a resolution of about 25 microns and requiring about 22 hours.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This scan was part of the human organ atlas which has X-ray tomography scans of other organs in the human body with the same resolution.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A crucial idea for magnetic resonance imaging is that the net magnetization vector can be moved by exposing the spin system to energy of a frequency equal to the energy difference between the spin states (e.g., by a radio frequency pulse).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] If enough energy is delivered to the system, it is possible to make the net magnetization vector orthogonal to that of the external magnetic field.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroradiology often follows a neurological examination in which a physician has found cause to more deeply investigate a patient who has or may have a neurological disorder.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Common clinical indications for neuroimaging include head trauma, stroke like symptoms e.g.: sudden weakness/numbness in one half of body, difficulty talking or walking; seizures, sudden onset severe headache, sudden change in level of consciousness for unclear reasons.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Another indication for neuroradiology is CT-, MRI- and PET-guided stereotactic surgery or radiosurgery for treatment of intracranial tumors, arteriovenous malformations and other surgically treatable conditions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] One of the more common neurological problems which a person may experience is simple syncope.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Neuroradiology is not indicated for patients with stable headaches which are diagnosed as migraine.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Studies indicate that presence of migraine does not increase a patient's risk for intracranial disease.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A diagnosis of migraine which notes the absence of other problems, such as papilledema, would not indicate a need for radiological investigations.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In the course of conducting a careful diagnosis, the physician should consider whether the headache has a cause other than the migraine and might require radiological investigations.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Computed tomography of the head (CT scanning of the head) uses a series of X-rays taken from many different directions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Typically used for quickly viewing brain injuries, CT scanning uses a computer program that performs a numerical integral calculation (the inverse Radon transform) on the measured X-ray series to estimate how much of an X-ray beam is absorbed in a small volume of the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Typically the information is presented as cross-sections of the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain uses magnetic fields and radio waves to produce high quality two- or three-dimensional images of the brain and its structures without the use of ionizing radiation (X-rays) or radioactive tracers.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The record for the highest spatial resolution of a whole intact brain (postmortem) is 100 microns, from Massachusetts General Hospital.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The data was published in *Scientific Data* on 30 October 2019.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Positron emission tomography (PET) and brain positron emission tomography, measure emissions from radioactively labeled metabolically active chemicals that have been injected into the bloodstream.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The emission data are computer-processed to produce 2- or 3-dimensional images of the distribution of the chemicals throughout the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The positron emitting radioisotopes used are produced by a cyclotron, and chemicals are labeled with these radioactive atoms.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The labeled compound, called a radiotracer, is injected into the bloodstream and eventually makes its way to the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Sensors in the PET scanner detect the radioactivity as the compound accumulates in various regions of the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A computer uses the data gathered by the sensors to create multicolored 2- or 3-dimensional images that show where the compound acts in the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Especially useful are a wide array of ligands used to map different aspects of neurotransmitter activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The most commonly used PET tracer is a labeled form of glucose (FDG).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The greatest benefit of PET scanning is that different compounds can show blood flow and oxygen and glucose metabolism in the tissues of the working brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] These measurements reflect the amount of brain activity in the various regions of the brain and allow to learn more about how the brain works.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] PET scans were superior to all other metabolic imaging methods in terms of resolution and speed of completion (as little as 30 seconds) when they first became available.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The improved resolution permitted better study to be made as to the area of the brain activated by a particular task.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The biggest drawback of PET scanning is that because the radioactivity decays rapidly, it is limited to monitoring short tasks.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Before fMRI technology came online, PET scanning was the preferred method of functional (as opposed to structural) brain imaging, and it continues to make large contributions to neuroscience.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] PET scanning is also used for diagnosis of brain disease, most notably brain tumors, epilepsy, and neuron-damaging diseases which cause dementia (such as Alzheimer's disease) all cause great changes in brain metabolism, which in turn causes easily detectable changes in PET scans.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] FDG-PET scanning is also often used in assessment of patients with epilepsy who continue to have seizures despite adequate medical treatment.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In focal epilepsy, where seizures begin in a small part of the brain before spreading elsewhere, it is one of the many modalities used to identify the region of brain responsible for seizure onset.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Typically, the area of brain where seizures begin is dysfunctional even when patient is not having a seizure and uptakes less glucose, hence less FDG compared to healthy brain regions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This information can help plan for epilepsy surgery as a treatment for drug resistant epilepsy.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Other radiotracers have also been used to identify areas of seizure onset though they are not available commercially for clinical use.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] These include 11C-flumazenil, 11C-alpha-methyl-L-tryptophan, 11C-methionine, 11C-cerfentanil.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) is similar to PET and uses gamma ray-emitting radioisotopes and a gamma camera to record data that a computer uses to construct two- or three-dimensional images of active brain regions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] SPECT relies on an injection of radioactive tracer, or "SPECT agent," which is rapidly taken up by the brain but does not redistribute.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Uptake of SPECT agent is nearly 100% complete within 30 to 60 seconds, reflecting cerebral blood flow (CBF) at the time of injection.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] These properties of SPECT make it particularly well-suited for epilepsy imaging, which is usually made difficult by problems with patient movement and variable seizure types.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] SPECT provides a "snapshot" of cerebral blood flow since scans can be acquired after seizure termination (so long as the radioactive tracer was injected at the time of the seizure).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A significant limitation of SPECT is its poor resolution (about 1 cm) compared to that of MRI.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Today, SPECT machines with Dual Detector Heads are commonly used, although Triple Detector Head machines are available in the marketplace.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Tomographic reconstruction, (mainly used for functional "snapshots" of the brain) requires multiple projections from Detector Heads which rotate around the human skull, so some researchers have developed 6 and 11 Detector Head SPECT machines to cut imaging time and give higher resolution.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Like PET, SPECT also can be used to differentiate different kinds of disease processes which produce dementia, and it is increasingly used for this purpose.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] SPECT scan using Isoflupane labeled with I-123 (also called DaT scan) is useful in differentiating Parkinson's disease from other causes of tremor.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] SPECT scan is also used in evaluation of drug resistant epilepsy.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This uses Tc99 labeled hexamethyl-propylene amine oxime (Tc99HMPAO) or ethyl cysteinate dimer ( Tc99 ECD) as the tracers.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The radiotracer is injected into the patient's vein as soon as the start of a seizure is detected and scanning is done within few hours after the seizure is over.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This technique is called ictal SPECT and relies on the increased CBF in areas of seizure onset during the seizure.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Interictal SPECT is a scan done using the same tracers but during a time when the patient is not having a seizure.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In between seizures, a reduction in CBF is seen in areas of seizure onset and is not as pronounced as the blood flow increase during the seizure.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Cranial ultrasound is usually only used in babies, whose open fontanelles provide acoustic windows allowing ultrasound imaging of the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Advantages include the absence of ionising radiation and the possibility of bedside scanning, but the lack of soft-tissue detail means MRI is preferred for some conditions.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and arterial spin labeling (ASL) relies on the paramagnetic properties of oxygenated and deoxygenated hemoglobin to see images of changing blood flow in the brain associated with neural activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This allows images to be generated that reflect which brain structures are activated (and how) during the performance of different tasks or at resting state.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] According to the oxygenation hypothesis, changes in oxygen usage in regional cerebral blood flow during cognitive or behavioral activity can be associated with the regional neurons as being directly related to the cognitive or behavioral tasks being attended.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Most fMRI scanners allow subjects to be presented with different visual images, sounds and touch stimuli, and to make different actions such as pressing a button or moving a joystick.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Consequently, fMRI can be used to reveal brain structures and processes associated with perception, thought and action.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The resolution of fMRI is about 2-3 millimeters at present, limited by the spatial spread of the hemodynamic response to neural activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] It has largely superseded PET for the study of brain activation patterns.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] PET, however, retains the significant advantage of being able to identify specific brain receptors (or transporters) associated with particular neurotransmitters through its ability to image radiolabeled receptor "ligands" (receptor ligands are any chemicals that stick to receptors).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] There is also significant concern regarding the validity of some of the statistics used in fMRI analyses; hence, the validity of conclusions drawn from many fMRI studies.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] With between 72% and 90% accuracy where chance would achieve 0.8%, fMRI techniques can decide which of a set of known images the subject is viewing.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Recent studies on machine learning in psychiatry have used fMRI to build machine learning models that can discriminate between individuals with or without suicidal behaviour.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Imaging studies in conjunction with machine learning algorithms may help identify new markers in neuroimaging that could allow stratification based on patients' suicide risk and help develop the best therapies and treatments for individual patients.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Diffuse optical imaging (DOI) or diffuse optical tomography (DOT) is a medical imaging modality which uses near infrared light to generate images of the body.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The technique measures the optical absorption of haemoglobin, and relies on the absorption spectrum of haemoglobin varying with its oxygenation status.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] High-density diffuse optical tomography (HD-DOT) has been compared directly to fMRI using response to visual stimulation in subjects studied with both techniques, with reassuringly similar results.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] HD-DOT has also been compared to fMRI in terms of language tasks and resting state functional connectivity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Event-related optical signal (EROS) is a brain-scanning technique which uses infrared light through optical fibers to measure changes in optical properties of active areas of the cerebral cortex.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] EROS can pinpoint activity in the brain within millimeters (spatially) and within milliseconds (temporally).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Its biggest downside is the inability to detect activity more than a few centimeters deep.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] EROS is a new, relatively inexpensive technique that is non-invasive to the test subject.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] It was developed at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign where it is now used in the Cognitive Neuroimaging Laboratory of Dr.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Magnetoencephalography (MEG) is an imaging technique used to measure the magnetic fields produced by electrical activity in the brain via extremely sensitive devices such as superconducting quantum interference devices (SQUIDs) or spin exchange relaxation-free (SERF) magnetometers.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] MEG offers a very direct measurement of neural electrical activity (compared to fMRI for example) with very high temporal resolution but relatively low spatial resolution.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The advantage of measuring the magnetic fields produced by neural activity is that they are likely to be less distorted by surrounding tissue (particularly the skull and scalp) compared to the electric fields measured by electroencephalography (EEG).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Specifically, it can be shown that magnetic fields produced by electrical activity are not affected by the surrounding head tissue, when the head is modeled as a set of concentric spherical shells, each being an isotropic homogeneous conductor.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Real heads are non-spherical and have largely anisotropic conductivities (particularly white matter and skull).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] While skull anisotropy has a negligible effect on MEG (unlike EEG), white matter anisotropy strongly affects MEG measurements for radial and deep sources.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Note, however, that the skull was assumed to be uniformly anisotropic in this study, which is not true for a real head: the absolute and relative thicknesses of diploë and tables layers vary among and within the skull bones.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] This makes it likely that MEG is also affected by the skull anisotropy, although probably not to the same degree as EEG.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] There are many uses for MEG, including assisting surgeons in localizing a pathology, assisting researchers in determining the function of various parts of the brain, neurofeedback, and others.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Functional ultrasound imaging (fUS) is a medical ultrasound imaging technique of detecting or measuring changes in neural activities or metabolism, for example, the loci of brain activity, typically through measuring blood flow or hemodynamic changes.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Functional ultrasound relies on Ultrasensitive Doppler and ultrafast ultrasound imaging which allows high sensitivity blood flow imaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In June 2021, researchers reported the development of the first modular quantum brain scanner which uses magnetic imaging and could become a novel whole-brain scanning approach.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] fMRI is commonly classified as a minimally-to-moderate risk due to its non-invasiveness compared to other imaging methods. fMRI uses blood oxygenation level dependent (BOLD)-contrast in order to produce its form of imaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] BOLD-contrast is a naturally occurring process in the body so fMRI is often preferred over imaging methods that require radioactive markers to produce similar imaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A concern in the use of fMRI is its use in individuals with medical implants or devices and metallic items in the body.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The magnetic resonance (MR) emitted from the equipment can cause failure of medical devices and attract metallic objects in the body if not properly screened for.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Currently, the FDA classifies medical implants and devices into three categories, depending on MR-compatibility: MR-safe (safe in all MR environments), MR-unsafe (unsafe in any MR environment), and MR-conditional (MR-compatible in certain environments, requiring further information).
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The CT scan was introduced in the 1970s and quickly became one of the most widely used methods of imaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A CT scan can be performed in under a second and produce rapid results for clinicians, with its ease of use leading to an increase in CT scans performed in the United States from 3 million in 1980 to 62 million in 2007.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Clinicians oftentimes take multiple scans, with 30% of individuals undergoing at least 3 scans in one study of CT scan usage.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] CT scans can expose patients to levels of radiation 100-500 times higher than traditional x-rays, with higher radiation doses producing better resolution imaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] While easy to use, increases in CT scan use, especially in asymptomatic patients, is a topic of concern since patients are exposed to significantly high levels of radiation.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] In PET scans, imaging does not rely on intrinsic biological processes, but relies on a foreign substance injected into the bloodstream traveling to the brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Patients are injected with radioisotopes that are metabolized in the brain and emit positrons to produce a visualization of brain activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The amount of radiation a patient is exposed to in a PET scan is relatively small, comparable to the amount of environmental radiation an individual is exposed to across a year.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] PET radioisotopes have limited exposure time in the body as they commonly have very short half-lives (~2 hours) and decay rapidly.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Currently, fMRI is a preferred method of imaging brain activity compared to PET, since it does not involve radiation, has a higher temporal resolution than PET, and is more readily available in most medical settings.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] The high temporal resolution of MEG and EEG allow these methods to measure brain activity down to the millisecond.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] Both MEG and EEG do not require exposure of the patient to radiation to function.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] EEG electrodes detect electrical signals produced by neurons to measure brain activity and MEG uses oscillations in the magnetic field produced by these electrical currents to measure activity.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A barrier in the widespread usage of MEG is due to pricing, as MEG systems can cost millions of dollars.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] EEG is a much more widely used method to achieve such temporal resolution as EEG systems cost much less than MEG systems.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/brain-imaging] A disadvantage of EEG and MEG is that both methods have poor spatial resolution when compared to fMRI.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The **Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics** (German: *Max-Planck-Institut für Psycholinguistik*; Dutch: *Max Planck Instituut voor Psycholinguïstiek*) is a research institute located on the campus of Radboud University Nijmegen in Nijmegen, Gelderland, the Netherlands.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The institute was founded in 1980 by Dutch psycholinguist Pim Levelt and is dedicated exclusively to psycholinguistics.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] It is one of the few institutes of the Max Planck Society situated outside Germany.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] According to the ranking of Web of World Research Centers, the institute ranks second amongst all Max Planck Institutes (MPI) in terms of visibility and eighth in terms of size.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The institute specializes in language comprehension, language production, language acquisition, language and genetics, and the relation between language and cognition.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Its mission is to undertake basic research into the psychological, social, and biological foundations of language.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The goal is to understand how human minds and brains process language, how language interacts with other aspects of mind, and how to learn languages of quite different types.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The MPI for Psycholinguistics is a globally recognized center of linguistics and presents with its international archive of endangered languages a significant contribution to the preservation of the common heritage of mankind.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Offering about 50 projects on the Internet, the archive has been sponsored since 2000 by the Volkswagen Foundation.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The MPI for Psycholinguistics has four primary organizational units besides research groups: Language and Genetics, Language Development, Neurobiology of Language, and Psychology of Language.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Established in October 2010, the language and genetics department is headed by Simon E.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The department takes advantage of the latest innovations in molecular methods to discover how the human genome helps to build a language-ready brain.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] It aims to uncover the DNA variations, which ultimately affect different facets of human communicative abilities, not only in children with language-related disorders but also in the general population.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Its work attempts to bridge the gaps between genes, brains, speech, and language, by integrating molecular findings with data from other levels of analysis, including cell biology, experimental psychology, and neuroimaging.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] In addition, it hopes to trace the evolutionary history and worldwide diversity of key genes, which may shed new light on language origins.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The original Language Acquisition Department (1980-2015) investigated processes of language acquisition and use.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The department combined attention to both first and second languages, researching production as well as comprehension of speakers of different ages and cultures, and the developmental relationship between language and cognition.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The focus was on morpho-syntax, semantics, and discourse structure.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Headed by Wolfgang Klein, Language Acquisition previously launched three institute projects: Information Structure in Language Acquisition, Categories in Language and Cognition, and Multimodal Interaction.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The Language Acquisition Department returned in 2016 as the Language Development Department, headed by Caroline F.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The Neurobiology of Language Department, headed by Peter Hagoort, focuses on the study of language production, language comprehension, and language acquisition from a cognitive neuroscience perspective.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] This includes using neuroimaging, behavioral, and virtual reality techniques to investigate the language system and its neural underpinnings.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Research facilities at the MPI include a high-density electroencephalography (EEG) lab, a virtual reality laboratory, and several behavioral laboratories.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Having a part of the department stationed at the Donders Institute for Brain, Cognition and Behaviour, Centre for Cognitive Neuroimaging, it has access to a whole-head 275-channel MEG system, MRI scanners at 1.5, 3 and 7 tesla, a TMS lab, and several additional EEG laboratories.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The Psychology of Language Department, headed by Antje S.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Meyer, identifies characteristics of the cognitive system that determine behavior in a broad range of linguistic tasks and the relationships between language production, comprehension, and learning via speaking, listening, and cognition.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The department also studies variability in adult language production and comprehension.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Using various approaches, the Psychology of Language utilizes a combination of experimental and correlational work and inclusion of diverse samples of participants.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] With such methods, it has close links to the Language and Genetics and Neurobiology of Language departments.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The Language and Cognition Department (1994-2017), headed by Stephen C.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Levinson, investigated the relationship between language, culture, and general cognition, making use of the natural laboratory of language variation.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] In this way, the research aimed to bring the perspective of language diversity to a range of central problems in the language sciences.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Languages were described (sometimes for the first time) based on field data.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] These field experiments helped to extend the corpora (a.k.a.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] *digital archive*) of natural language research.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The department used a diversity of methods that spanned many area, including linguistic description, ethnography, child development perspectives, psycholinguistic experimentation, conversation analysis, corpus statistics, brain imaging, phylogenetics, and linguistic data mining.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The department's overarching research focus was on typology within interactional linguistics.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] The Language Comprehension Department (1993-2013), headed by Anne Cutler, undertook empirical investigation and computational modeling of the understanding of spoken language.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Until 2009, the work within the department was largely divided between two research projects: decoding continuous speech and phonological learning for speech perception; thereafter, most work was in the project called *Mechanisms and Representations in Comprehending Speech*.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Their work is motivated by the idea that there is a psychological basis of human communication that develops ontogenetically prior to language and can be first expressed in gestures.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Started in 2009, the research group investigates language diversity and change as part of an integrated cultural evolutionary system.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Van Valin, Jr., tries to determine the role of information structure in explaining cross-linguistic differences in grammatical systems out of the idea that the interaction of pragmatics and grammar happens on several levels and differs from language to language.
[src:max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics/max-planck-institute-for-psycholinguistics] Another major task of the group is to investigate and re-evaluate the status of the information structure primitives (topic, focus, contrast, etc.) as cross-linguistically valid categories.
